We are storing the string in a buffer that is null-terminated, but the string itself does not contain the null? We are going to traverse the string until the null terminator? That would include the null? which is not part of the string. How did the Python program get the characters? It did: list(input()) -> which returns a list of the characters in the string (without the null). So in C, we must traverse the string by its length (which we can get with strlen) and not include the null. 7. For each character in the string (from index=0 to index=len-1):

          if the char is 'g': ... 
          else if the char is 'p': ... 
          else: do nothing.

   8. Then output the score. Since the string contains only digits and space, the score remains 0. Therefore, we output 0. However, note: what if the string representation of the numbers contains the letter 'e'? For example, if we use %d and the number is too big? No, we are using %d and %lld, so for integers they will be printed in decimal without exponent. Example: 10000000000 -> printed as "10000000000", which is digits only. Therefore, the string is safe. Implementation:

   We'll do:

        #include <stdio.h>
        #include <stdlib.h>
        #include <string.h>

        // Comparison function for qsort
        int compare(const void *a, const void *b) {
            return (*(int*)a - *(int*)b);
        }

        int main() {
            int n;
            scanf("%d", &n);
            int *arr = (int*)malloc(n * sizeof(int));
            for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
                scanf("%d", &arr[i]);
            }

            // Sort the array
            qsort(arr, n, sizeof(int), compare);

            long long diff = (long long)arr[n-1] - arr[0];
            long long count;

            if (arr[0] == arr[n-1]) {
                count = (long long)n * (n-1) / 2;
            } else {
                // Count the frequency of the min
                int count_min = 1;
                int i = 1; while (i < n && arr[i] == arr[0]) {
                    count_min++;
                    i++;
                }

                // Count the frequency of the max
                int count_max = 1;
                int j = n-2;
                while (j >= 0 && arr[j] == arr[n-1]) {
                    count_max++;
                    j--;
                }
                count = (long long)count_min * count_max;
            }

            // Now, we have two numbers: diff and count. Format them into a string without newline. char buffer[256];
            sprintf(buffer, "%lld %lld", diff, count);
            // This string does not have a newline.

            // Now, run the second program on this string. int num_g = 0, num_p = 0, score = 0;
            int len = strlen(buffer);
            for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
                char c = buffer[i]; if (c == 'g') {
                    if (num_g > num_p) {
                        score++;
                        num_p++;
                    } else {
                        num_g++;
                    }
                } else if (c == 'p') {
                    if (num_g > num_p) {
                        num_p++;
                    } else {
                        score--;
                        num_g++;
                    }
                }
                // For any other character, do nothing.
            }

            printf("%d\n", score);

            free(arr);
            return 0;
        } However, note: the second program in the original Python code had an else branch for 'p'? Actually, the Python code: if x == 'g':
            if num_g - num_p > 0:
                score += 1
                num_p += 1
            else:
                score = score   # do nothing
                num_g += 1
        elif x == 'p':
            if num_g - num_p > 0:
                score = score   # do nothing
                num_p += 1
            else:
                score -= 1
                num_g += 1

   We can rewrite the C code accordingly. But note: in the 'g' branch, when we do nothing to score, we still update num_g? Actually, in the 'g' branch:
        if (num_g > num_p) -> then we do: score++ and num_p++.
        else: we do: num_g++. In the 'p' branch:
        if (num_g > num_p) -> then we do: num_p++ (and score unchanged)
        else: we do: score-- and num_g++. So the above C code for the second program is equivalent.
